 API Endpoints:

 Auth:

- `POST /api/login/`

 Users:

- `GET /api/users/`
- `POST /api/users/`

 Financial Records:

- `GET /api/transactions/records/`
- `POST /api/transactions/records/`
- `PUT /api/transactions/records/{id}/`
- `DELETE /api/transactions/records/{id}/`

 Dashboard:

- `GET /api/transactions/dashboard/`
- `GET /api/transactions/summary/`


Design Decisions & Assumptions:

- Each financial record belongs to one user
- Users can only access their own data unless they are admins
- Transactions are treated as independent entries
- Categories are kept simple (no separate model for now)

Possible Improvements:

If extended further, the following could be added:

- Pagination
- Swagger/OpenAPI documentation
- Docker support
- Unit tests
- More advanced filtering


Final Thoughts:

This project focuses on building a clean and functional backend with proper structure, access control, and data handling.

The goal was not to overcomplicate things, but to demonstrate a solid understanding of backend development fundamentals in a practical way.


